T1  - The Breakup of Nations: A Political Economy Analysis*
PY  - 1997
Y1  - 1997/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355300555420
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 112
IS  - 4
SP  - 1057
EP  - 1090
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper develops a model of the breakup or unification of nations. In each nation the decision to separate is taken by majority voting. A basic trade-off between the efficiency gains of unification and the costs in terms of loss of control on political decisions is highlighted. The model emphasizes political conflicts over redistribution policies. The main results of the paper are i) when income distributions vary across regions and the efficiency gains from unification are small, separation occurs in equilibrium; and ii) when all factors of production are perfectly mobile, all incentives for separation disappear.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355300555420
ER  - 



